Passing Artifacts in Argo Workflows

George Novack

4 hours ago·7 min read

Last time, I took a look at Argo, and walked through the basics of how to create and run a simple containerized workflow. In this article, I’ll dive a little deeper into the different ways that we can pass data between multiple steps in an Argo Workflow.

Setup

If you would like to follow along with the examples below, you’ll need access to a Kubernetes cluster with Argo installed. If you need any help with this setup, feel free to follow the Setting up a Kubernetes Cluster section in my previous article: Creating Containerized Workflows with Argo

Parameters and Artifacts

A key feature of any workflow engine is the ability to pass data between mulitple steps in a workflow, using the output of one step as the the input to a subsequent step. Using Argo, there are two different ways that we can pass data between steps: Parameters and Artifacts.

Working with Parameters

Parameter passing is the simpler of the two options, and allows us to pass string values between steps in a workflow. Let’s see how this works with a quick example. We’ll create a workflow that generates two random integers, then passes these as parameters to a final step that will compute their difference.

We will first create a Python script and a barebones Dockerfile to containerize the random integer generation step:

Then a similar Python script and Dockerfile for the step that calculates the difference:

Note: I built and pushed the two above container images to the gnovack/argo-artifacts-python-rng and gnovack/argo-artifacts-python-subtract public repositories. If you are following along but do not want to use these public images, you will need to build and push the images to a repository you own, and then modify all of the workflow YAML manifests to use the images you created.

Now we will use these steps together to create a workflow. Here is the YAML manifest that defines our simple random number subtraction workflow:

This workflow manifest defines three templates:

  • python-rng: This template executes the random number generator container image. It specifies an output parameter named output-param-1, whose value is populated from the /tmp/output file on the container file system (there is nothing special about the path /tmp/output/, this just needs to match the path that we write our result to in the Python random number generation script).
  • python-subtract: This template executes the subtraction container image. It also specifies an output parameter that is populated from a file called /tmp/output. Additionally, it specifies two input parameters called value-1 and value-2, which are passed as arguments to the subtraction container. This allows our Python script running in this container to access the inputs using sys.argv like so:
value_1, value_2 = int(sys.argv[1]), int(sys.argv[2])
  • steps: This steps template handles chaining the other templates together into a workflow. It executes two instances of the python-rng template in parallel (notice that the steps property on line 37 contains a list of lists. Steps defined in the inner lists run in parallel, while the outer lists of steps run in sequence). Next, it executes the python-subtract template, passing the output parameters of the random number generation steps as input parameters (lines 45–48).

We can execute this workflow using either the UI or the Argo CLI. The result will look something like this in the UI:

This workflow illustrates the basic way that we can pass data in the form of parameters between steps. There are, however, more complex ways that we can work with parameters in our workflows. Rather than simply passing on whatever values are output by each container, Argo allows us to write custom expressions to manipulate these outputs in our workflows.

For example, say we want to modify our subtraction workflow to output the absolute value of the difference between the two random integers, so that the workflow never returns a negative value. We can accomplish this by using an expression. There are many ways we could write this expression, but here we will replace the workflow outputs property (defined on line 50 in the YAML manifest above) with the following:

As you can see, we are able to use basic conditional and arithmetic operations in the expression, and we also have access to several built-in functions, such as the asInt function used here. You can find a full list of built-in functions in the Argo docs: https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/conditional-artifacts-parameters/#built-in-functions

Of course, in this case we could have achieved the same result by implementing this logic in the python script that is executed in our python-subtract container, but there are many situations where we may not want to modify the internal logic of a given step, especially if that step is used in many different workflows. The use of expressions can be a good way to keep our steps independent of any single workflow that uses them.

Working with Artifacts

We’ve seen how to use Parameters to pass string values between steps in a workflow, but oftentimes we will need to pass more than just strings. Many workflows will involve passing large datasets (e.g. in the form of CSV or Parquet files) between various data transformation steps. This is where Artifacts come in.

Setting up an artifact repository

Before we can start using artifacts in our workflows, we must first setup an artifact repository. There are a number of different storage solutions that can act as an artifact repository, including AWS S3, GCS, and Minio. I’ll be using S3 for these examples.

The first step is to create an S3 Bucket where Argo will store all of our artifacts:

aws s3api create-bucket --bucket gnovack-argo-artifacts --region us-west-2 --create-bucket-configuration LocationConstraint=us-west-2

Next, we will need to grant Argo access to this bucket. Since the Kubernetes cluster I am using is also running on AWS (I am using the same cluster setup outlined in Creating Containerized Workflows with Argo), this will involve making sure that the IAM role assumed by my cluster’s nodes has access to the bucket. For those not running their Kubernetes cluster on AWS EC2, you will need to create an access key that grants access to the bucket, then make this access key available to your cluster. Follow the Argo guide for more details: Configuring AWS S3

Using eksctl we can get the name of the IAM role assumed by the cluster nodes:

eksctl get iamidentitymapping --cluster {CLUSTER_NAME}

With the role name output by the command above, we can then run the following to grant our cluster nodes full access to S3:

aws iam attach-role-policy --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonS3FullAccess --role-name {ROLE_NAME}

Finally, we can set this S3 bucket as the default artifact repository by creating a config map named artifact-repositories like so:

Using Artifacts in a Workflow

Now, with an artifact repository configured, let’s see how to use artifacts in an Argo workflow.

We’ll create a similar random number generation script like before, but this time instead of writing out a single output line to a text file, we will write out an entire CSV file.

Then we will create a second step that reads in a CSV file, calculates the sum of the columns, then outputs another CSV file with a single column containing the results.

We then define a workflow using these two steps:

This workflow is very similar to the subtract_random_numbers workflow that we looked at earlier; however, here we are using artifacts in place of parameters to pass files between steps in the workflow.

When we execute this workflow, we will see that the output is no longer a simple string value like before. Instead, it is an artifact that can be downloaded from the Argo Server UI.

Additionally, if we check the S3 bucket that was specified in the Artifact Repository definition, we will see directories for the two artifacts (Random number CSV and Sum CSV) that were used in the workflow.

By default, the underlying artifacts within these directories are stored as GZIP compressed Tar files. This behavior can be modified by providing a value for the archive property of any output artifact.

As we can see from this example, artifacts in Argo workflows work much like parameters, but allow us to pass files instead of strings between steps. Of course, we could have used parameters to pass the S3 file paths from one step to the next; however, this would have coupled our step logic (i.e. the Python code running in each step) to the underlying artifact repository (i.e. S3), because each step would then need to know how to authenticate to this S3 bucket and how to properly read the appropriate file(s).

By using artifacts, we are able to abstract away the underlying storage solution, allowing each individual step to interact with stored artifacts as if they were simply on the local filesystem of that step’s container.

Wrapping up

In this article, we looked at the distinction between parameters and artifacts when passing data through an Argo workflow. We saw how to use parameters to pass string values between steps, then we walked through an example of using artifacts to pass files from one step to the next, using AWS S3 as an artifact repository.

I hope these examples can provide a basic understanding of how we can pas parameters and artifacts in Argo. You can find all of the code from the examples in this GitHub repo: https://github.com/gnovack/argo-artifacts-passing

Thanks for reading. Feel free to reach out with any questions or comments.
